Wizard: Ice Shock (4.15)<br>
Difference: .85<br>
<br>
Level 39<br>
Mage: no blast (Expel Summoned 4.5)<br>
Wizard: Lightning Shock (4.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
Difference: n/a<br>
<br>
I think that pretty well covers lower levels.  <br>
<br>
Average difference in time: .47<br>
Biggest time difference: .85 (the level in question)<br>
<br>
How long do you suppose your pet and damage shields will take to fill that gap?  Yeah, one hit, maybe two if its a bad one.  Mages outdamage Wizards in very, very short order.  The only time a Wizard really is going to be able to outdamage a Mage at these levels is at level 1 (no pet) or by casting a single spell that kills the monster before the mage's pet can engage.  Using the staff of temperate flux, the Wizard could probably chaincast a faster blast and get the kill if the pet wasn't hitting very well or was casting a lot - especially nondamaging spells.<br>
<br>
I hope that makes things a little more clear.  There was no good reason for having the damage set up in this way, I am still convinced it was done because of a lack of context.  They adjusted the numbers without comparing them for Wizard and Magician.<br>
