<br>
The casting times are so close together that it will take about 4-5 casts before the Wizard can get ONE more spell off than the Mage.  If the Wizard has the SOTF it will take 2-3 of them.  The edge in speed, quite honestly, is absolutely not a major issue, except at level 34.  And its still less than 1 second difference.<br>
<br>
&quot;Also, I'm not a little confused about how you came up with .12 as your average, it looks to me as if you counted the levels where magicians got no nuke at all as a difference of 0. Which leads me back to the level one shock comparison.&quot;<br>
<br>
No, I left them off deliberately (as stated above), but the number looks wrong to me too, I'll do it again and edit the results if I get a different average.<br>
<br>
This statement bothers me a great deal though:<br>
<br>
&quot;I also may have been a bit careless with my use of the word &quot;significantly.&quot; I consider nuking slow enough such that my pet is required to break even with a wizard significant. I don't believe wizards should be outdamaging a magician+pet in the short term by much, if at all.. though who is ultimately more effective is highly dependant on the situation and skill of the player(which is as it should be, imo).&quot;<br>
<br>
I see two problems here.  First, your belief that you'll need a pet to equal my short term damage a significant difference, and second that you &quot;I don't believe wizards should be outdamaging a magician+pet in the short term by much, if at all.&quot;<br>
<br>
See, you have a pretty odd philosophy about what a Wizard should be.  Apparently you are of the opinion that Magicians should be better than Wizards in combat, and that a Wizards only edge should be as a taxi, moving the characters to where they need to go.  How you can even remotely attempt to justify wanting to continue the already absurd situation where Mages can comfortably outdamage Wizards in the short term and ENORMOUSLY in the long term I can't imagine.<br>
<br>
Why, precisely, would anyone ever want a Wizard in a group again?<br>
